	affiliations = {University of Toronto, Canada},
	abstract = {The power system is a complex entity comprising of a large number of components such as loads, generators, and the control and comunication backbones, which are scattered around vast geographical regions. This complex system is challenging to control due to several factors, including multitude of components, the multiple objectives the control system needs to achieve, and the large number of inputs and outputs of the system. The modern approach to deal with such challenges in the control of the power system is turning the power system into a Smart Grid, the vision for the future of the power system. As a fairly new concept, there is no universally accepted definition for the smart grid. However, various definitions share a number of elements of which the smart grid will take advantage: (i) information technology, (ii) comunications, and (iii) power electronics. These comon elements reflect in the five key technology areas of the smart grid, which are (i) integration comunications, (ii) advanced components, (iii) advanced control methods, (iv) sensing and measurement, and (v) improved interfaces and decision support systems. The smart grid vision requires the active distribution network hosting a microgrid to remain operational even when the microgrid becomes islanded. The goal of this paper is to develop a secondary voltage controller for maintaining the stable operation of a microgrid, as a subsystem within an active distribution network, subsequent to the islanding process. In this work, the problem of voltage control of distributed energy resource (DER) units of a microgrid is interpreted as an application of the rendezvous problem in the distributed control of autonomous mobile vehicles (with dq-components of the voltage interpreted as equivalent to the xy-coordinates of vehicles). In the rendezvous problem, a potential function is defined for each unit such that it incorporates the voltage regulation goals and encodes the "distance" between the voltages of each unit and the target voltage. The potential functions assume their minima when each unit is at the prescribed distance from the target voltage and other units (in case there are constraints regarding other units). Therefore, the effort to minimize these potential functions corresponds to finding a solution to the rendezvous problem, and hence the microgrid reference points. The proposed method is implemented on a test system, and the system response is evaluated.},
